  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The ceremony described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 24:3-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is called \"the covenant which Jehovah made with Israel\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 24:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was opened by Moses, who recited to the people \"all the words of Jehovah\" (i.e., not the decalogue, for the people had heard this directly from the mouth of God Himself, but the words in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 20:22-26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and \"all the rights\" (ch. 21-23); whereupon the people answered unanimously (אחד קול), \"All the words which Jehovah hath spoken will we do.\" This constituted the preparation for the conclusion of the covenant. It was necessary that the people should not only know what the Lord imposed upon them in the covenant about to be made with them, and what He promised them, but that they should also declare their willingness to perform what was imposed upon them. The covenant itself was commenced by Moses writing all the words of Jehovah in \"the book of the covenant\" (",
